{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cosine similarity measures the angle between two vectors, ignoring their magnitudes. Two texts encoded into vectors will have high cosine similarity if they point in the same direction in embedding space — which happens when they carry the same semantic content — regardless of how long or short the originals were."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Cosine similarity geometry: two vectors a and b with angle θ, range table, and implementation code showing the dot-product shortcut when normalised."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Formula"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For two vectors "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "a"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "b"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "n"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " dimensions:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{cos}(\\theta) = \\frac{\\mathbf{a} \\cdot \\mathbf{b}}{\\|\\mathbf{a}\\| \\cdot \\|\\mathbf{b}\\|} = \\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i b_i}{\\sqrt{\\sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i^2} \\cdot \\sqrt{\\sum_{i=1}^{n} b_i^2}}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The result is the cosine of the angle θ between the two vectors. It ranges from −1 to 1 in theory, but for most embedding models it falls in the range [0, 1] in practice because the models are trained with contrastive objectives that push unrelated texts toward orthogonal directions (cos θ ≈ 0), not opposite ones."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Computing Cosine Similarity in NumPy"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\n\na = np.array([0.8, 0.6, 0.0])\nb = np.array([0.6, 0.8, 0.1])\n\n# Full formula\nsim = np.dot(a, b) / (np.linalg.norm(a) * np.linalg.norm(b))\nprint(f\"cosine similarity: {sim:.4f}\")   # 0.9606\n\n# Pairwise similarity matrix for a batch of vectors\nvecs = np.vstack([a, b, np.array([0.1, 0.0, 0.99])])\n\ndef cosine_matrix(vecs: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    norms = np.linalg.norm(vecs, axis=1, keepdims=True)\n    normalised = vecs / norms\n    return normalised @ normalised.T   # (N, N) matrix\n\nprint(cosine_matrix(vecs).round(3))\n# [[1.    0.961 0.003]\n#  [0.961 1.    0.081]\n#  [0.003 0.081 1.   ]]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Normalisation Trick"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When vectors are pre-normalised to unit length (‖v‖ = 1), the denominator in the cosine formula becomes 1·1 = 1, and cosine similarity reduces to the plain dot product:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{cos}(\\theta) = \\hat{\\mathbf{a}} \\cdot \\hat{\\mathbf{b}} \\quad \\text{where} \\quad \\hat{\\mathbf{v}} = \\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{\\|\\mathbf{v}\\|}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This is why "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "normalize_embeddings=True"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is used throughout the embedding examples — it unlocks dot-product search (faster) while preserving cosine semantics. FAISS "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "IndexFlatIP"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (inner product) becomes equivalent to cosine search when vectors are normalised at index time."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer\nimport numpy as np\n\nmodel = SentenceTransformer(\"BAAI/bge-m3\")\n\n# Normalise once at index time\nvecs = model.encode([\"Paris is the capital of France.\",\n                     \"The French capital is Paris.\",\n                     \"Python is a programming language.\"],\n                    normalize_embeddings=True)  # ← unit norm enforced here\n\n# Fast dot-product pairwise sim at query time\nsim = vecs @ vecs.T\nprint(sim.round(3))\n# [[1.    0.96  0.21]\n#  [0.96  1.    0.22]\n#  [0.21  0.22  1.  ]]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Cosine, Not Euclidean Distance?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Euclidean distance (L2) measures how far apart two points are in absolute terms. Cosine similarity measures the angle between them, ignoring how far from the origin they sit. For text, magnitude is not meaningful — a long document and a short document on the same topic should score similarly to a query, even though the long one has a larger norm."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\n\n# Two vectors pointing in the same direction but different magnitudes\na = np.array([3.0, 4.0])   # norm = 5\nb = np.array([0.6, 0.8])   # norm = 1 (a/5)\n\ncosine = np.dot(a, b) / (np.linalg.norm(a) * np.linalg.norm(b))\nl2_dist = np.linalg.norm(a - b)\n\nprint(f\"cosine: {cosine:.3f}\")    # 1.000 — identical direction\nprint(f\"L2 dist: {l2_dist:.3f}\")  # 4.000 — far apart in absolute terms"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cosine correctly identifies these as identical in direction (same topic). L2 distance would rank them as very different, which is wrong for semantic similarity."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Interpreting Cosine Scores"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The thresholds that matter depend on the embedding model, but the following guidance applies broadly for modern models trained for semantic search:"
          }
        ]
      },
