      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "These thresholds are model-dependent. Calibrate them by sampling 50–100 query-document pairs and labelling relevance by hand. Never use raw scores from one model to set thresholds for another."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Batch Computation with sklearn"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity\nimport numpy as np\n\n# Query batch vs document batch — no need to normalise first\nquery_vecs = np.random.randn(5, 1024)    # 5 queries\ndoc_vecs = np.random.randn(100, 1024)   # 100 documents\n\nsim_matrix = cosine_similarity(query_vecs, doc_vecs)  # shape (5, 100)\nprint(sim_matrix.shape)   # (5, 100)\n\n# Top-3 document indices for each query\ntop3 = np.argsort(sim_matrix, axis=1)[:, -3:][:, ::-1]\nprint(top3)  # shape (5, 3)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For large-scale pairwise computation (N > 10,000), prefer FAISS over sklearn — FAISS uses optimised BLAS routines and can distribute computation across GPU cores, reducing what would be minutes to milliseconds."
          }
        ]
      }
